@Node "The Menus" "ir-master26e.guide/The Menus"
@Next "The Toolbox"
@Prev "IR-Editor"
@Toc "IR-Editor"

The Menus
=========

Project
-------

@{i}Load...@{ui}
     Pops up a requester to load a saved project.

@{i}Save@{ui}
     Saves the current set of gadgets.

@{i}Save as...@{ui}
     Pops up a requester to save the current project.

     -----------------

@{i}Info@{ui}
     Gives some information about the used memory etc.

@{i}About@{ui}
     Credits...

     -----------------

@{i}Save Prefs@{ui}
     Saves the current settings, like position of the toolbox, size of
     project window...

@{i}Iconify@{ui}
     Closes screen, frees memory and puts an app icon onto the workbench

     ------------------

@{i}Quit@{ui}
     Quits the editor.

Edit
----

@{i}Cut@{ui}
     Cuts the selected Gadgets to a internal buffer. That means they
     will be deleted in the projectwindow and they can be pasted back
     anywehere.

@{i}Copy@{ui}
     Copies the selected Gadgets to a internal buffer. With "paste" you
     can insert this gadgets whereever you want.

     @{i}Note:@{ui} If the buffer is not empty and you cut/copy gadgets than the
     gadgets already in the buffer will be overwritten!

@{i}Paste@{ui}
     Paste back gadgets in the internal buffer.

@{i}Info@{ui}
     Gives an information of the gadgets which are stored in the buffer.

@{i}Flush@{ui}
     Clears the internal buffer.

Arrange
-------

   @{i}Note:@{ui} The reference gadget is always the @{i}first@{ui} selected. That means,
if I first select a big gad and than two small gads and I select @{i}clone
size@{ui} then all gadgets will be big...

@{i}Align Gadgets@{ui}
     aligns the selected gadgets
    @{i}Left@{ui}
          by the left edge or

    @{i}Top@{ui}
          by the top edge

@{i}Spread Gadgets@{ui}
    @{i}Horizontally@{ui}
          pops up a requester which asks how many pixels

    @{i}Vertically@{ui}
          should be placed between each of the selected gadgets in the
          selected direction...

@{i}Clone Size@{ui}
     Clones the sizes of the selected gadgets.

     ------------------

@{i}Coordinates@{ui}
     Opens/Closes the coordinates window. Only if one (!) gadget is
     selected the coordinates will be shown an can be directly edited.

Environment
-----------

@{i}Palette@{ui}
     Pops up the standard palette requester.

@{i}Font@{ui}
     Brings a font requester to the front. The selected font will only
     be used for the editor's screen. To change the font of the gadgets
     you have to use the font gadget in the toolbox.

@{i}Screenmode@{ui}
     Pops up a screenmode requester.

@{i}On Public Screen@{ui}
     Tries to close the IRMaster screen and reopen on the default
     public screen (mostly the wb).

@{i}Make Screen Public@{ui}
     Tries to close the current IRMaster GUI and reopen it as a public
     screen. The screen's name is "IRMaster".

@{i}Show IR-Code@{ui}
     Shows the IR-Code of the current gadget (if learned). It is
     designed like an oszillator, so you can easyly decide if the last
     learn action was successful!

     Length specifies the amount of memory which is used to send this
     command. The percentage shows how much of the memory reserved for
     this command is used.

@{i}Show Configuration@{ui}
     Shows the IR-configuration of the current gadet. For more
     information about the ir-configuration, See @{"Learning IR-Commands" Link "Learning IR-Commands"}.


@EndNode

@Node "The Toolbox" "ir-master26e.guide/The Toolbox"
@Next "Learning IR-Commands"
@Prev "The Menus"
@Toc "IR-Editor"

The Toolbox
===========

NewGadget
---------

   shortcut    @{b}F1@{ub}

   This function brings you to the "new gadget mode". You can see a
border attached to your pointer. With a mouseclick you can place the
new gadget.  A new gadget is always named @{b}New@{ub} and its size is 50 x 20
pixels.

Move Gadget(s)
--------------

   shortcut    @{b}F2@{ub}

   If you have some gadgets selected and you press the move button or
the move shortcut the selected gadgets will be represented by borders
which stick to your mouse pointer. With a click you can put the gadgets
to their new position.

Attache Grafic To Gadget
------------------------

   shortcut    @{b}F3@{ub}

   For each of the selected gadget a file requester pops to the front,
asking you for an icon/brush. This image will be used as gadget
imaginary.

Attache Text to Gadget
----------------------

   shortcut    @{b}F4@{ub}

   Pops a text requester to the front (for each gadget). You can type
any text. The length is not checked! It doesn't have any serious
consequences if the text is to wide for the gadget - it simply looks
awful.

Learn IR data
-------------

   shortcut    @{b}F5@{ub}

   With this gadget you can switch to the learn mode. The pointer will
remind you being in this mode. If you click a gadget, the Amiga is
frozen and waits for ir input to the IR-Sensor, see also
@{"Learning IR-Commands" Link "Learning IR-Commands"}.

Kill Gadget(s)
--------------

   shortcut    @{b}F6@{ub}

   Removes all selected gadgets @{i}without warning!@{ui} They are unrecoverably
lost.

Size Gadge
----------

   shortcut    @{b}F7@{ub}

   Switches to the size mode. A border is drawn - the lower right
corner sticks to the pointer. After a mouseclick the gadget will be
resized and the text/grafic will be centered in the gadget.

Load Backgound Grafic
---------------------

   shortcut    @{b}F8@{ub}

   Pops up a requester. Here you can select any @{b}.ilbm@{ub}-picture to be
used as background grafik for your remote control. This grafik's name
and path will be set in the tooltypes of the project when it is saved.

   Therefore the grafic must exist when the project is run. The palette
of the picture won't be used! I'm sure you like your wb-colors more!

   To clear the background again, click this gadget (or press @{b}F8@{ub}) and
select cancel in the filerequester.

Change Font
-----------

   shortcut    @{b}F9@{ub}

   Pops up a font requester. The selected font will be used for all the
selected gadgets. Make sure that this font is also available to the
IR_Runner.

Test IR Data
============

   shortcut    @{b}F10@{ub}

   Switches to the test mode. The pointer reminds you being in the test
mode.  @{i}Note:@{ui} To test ir commands, they must be learned before. To test
LControl or Rapid commands, LControl/Rapid must be running. See
@{"LControl & Rapid" Link "LControl & Rapid"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Learning IR-Commands" "ir-master26e.guide/Learning IR-Commands"
@Next "Drag & Drop"
@Prev "The Toolbox"
@Toc "IR-Editor"

Learning IR-Commands
====================

   Learn ir-commands:

   @{b}*@{ub} toggle to learn mode by pressing @{b}F5@{ub} or the equivalent gadget

   @{b}*@{ub} click on the gadget whose function you want to @{i}learn@{ui}
     ==> pointer is frozen...

   @{b}*@{ub} point your remote control to the ir-sensor
     (distance ca. 1-15 cm)

   @{b}*@{ub} hold the button down 'till the pointer can be moved again

   Test ir-commands

   @{b}*@{ub} switch to test mode by pressing @{b}F10@{ub} or the equivalent gadget

   @{b}*@{ub} hold transmitter in direction to the ir-receiver of the implement
     with a distance of 1-30 cm.

   @{b}*@{ub} click on the gadget you want to test
     ==> command will be sent

   @{i}Important notes@{ui}

  1. It is possible that the implement (like CD, Videorecorder, TV
     set,...) won't react on the ir-master the first time. In this case
     you have to change the parameters in the @{i}config-window@{ui}, See
     @{"The Menus" Link "The Menus"}.

     To get to the configrequester you must:

        @{b}*@{ub} click on the gadget the config should be changed

        @{b}*@{ub} open the config window          All the changes (but not
     wobbelcode) can be testet without learning it again.

     Config menu:

        - Configuration
         @{i}37 kHz@{ui}
               Carrier frequency of the ir signal is 37 kHz, matches
               for ca. 70% of all implements

         @{i}45 kHz@{ui}
               Carrier frequency is 45 kHz, matches for ca. 10%

         @{i}66 kHz@{ui}
               Carrier frequency is 66 kHz, matches for some implements

         @{i}Unpulsed@{ui}
               no carrier frequency, ca. 8%

         @{i}LControl@{ui}
               Directly sends commands to LControl to control video
               cameras via @{i}LANC@{ui}, See @{"LControl & Rapid" Link "LControl & Rapid"}.

         @{i}Rapid@{ui}
               Directly sends commands to Rapid to control video
               recorders via GSE-Rapid-Code, See @{"LControl & Rapid" Link "LControl & Rapid"}.

         @{i}Command@{ui}
               Executes a @{i}DOS@{ui}-Command. The text is interpreted as a
               line in the shell.

         @{i}Relais-Card@{ui}
               The IR-Master is also able to control a relai-card
               (special support for the relai-card which can be
               accessed by Konrad Electronic, Hirschau, Germany,
               art-nr: 192252-55 + 174025-55).

               This is a 4 channel ir receiver. With this receiver you
               can control any devices (like lamps, motors, etc.). Die
               ir-codes are already learded in by the IR-Master, so you
               do not have to relearn them.

               There are 2 number fields: The "RL:"- and "CH:"-field.
               The first is the bitcoded address of the relai(s) you
               want to activate and the second field is for the
               bitcoded address for the channel(s) you want to access.
               The "address" of the relai is 4 bit wide and the
               "address" of the channel is 6 bit wide. Each relai is
               represented by one bit (also the channels).

               Example
                  @{b}*@{ub} If you want to activate the relais 2 and 3 on
                    channel 0 you have to type the value of binary
                    %1100 (which is 12) into the relai field and 0 into
                    the channel field.

                  @{b}*@{ub} If you want to activate relai 1 on the channels 2,3
                    and 4, you have to type 1 into the relai field and
                    the value of %11100 (which is 28) into the channel
                    field.

        - Send command slider         This indicates how often the ir
          command should be sent. Normally 2-5 times is enough.

        -     @{i}Wobbelcode@{ui}         This is a special form of ir code. An
          implement which uses @{i}Wobbelcode@{ui} (e.g. Grundig tools) sends
          @{b}code A@{ub} the first time and the next time it sends (for the
          same function) @{b}code B@{ub}. In this case you have to learn twice.
          To learn this type of code you must click on @{i}Wobbelcode@{ui} in
          the config window and then click on learn and follow the
          messages in the status bar. You can recognize
          @{i}Wobbelcode@{ui}-implements when the implement reacts the first
          time at once but the second time it does nothing or it reacts
          very late.

  2. The learning of ir commands depends on the distance between remote
     control and ir sensor. After a faulty try you should attempt it
     again with different distances between 1 and 20cm.

  3. If the batteries of the remote control are weak you should use new
     batteries.

  4. In general @{i}all@{ui} impements can be controlled exept Telefunken.  For
     this type of implements we offer a special hardware - simply
     contact us and describe your implement.

  5. Finally: The parameters in the @{i}config window@{ui} are the most common
     but if it does not work - use trial and error. You can't damage
     your hardware by changing the parameters... believe me ;-)

   If you own a Akai, Blaupunkt, Fisher, Technics, Philips, Grundig,
Panasonic, Sony... you can learn the command set by nearly 100%.
(tested very (!) often...)

   YOU CAN ALSO USE UP TO 5 (WITH Y-ADAPTERS) IR TRANSMITTER IN YOUR
JOYSTICKPORT.


@EndNode

@Node "Drag & Drop" "ir-master26e.guide/Drag & Drop"
@Prev "Learning IR-Commands"
@Toc "IR-Editor"

Drag & Drop
===========

   @{b}Drag & Drop@{ub} is a Feature of AmigaDOS 2.04 and above which enables
you to drag an icon and drop it onto a special window causing a special
action. This is - of course - only possible when the applikation has
windows opened on the workbench.  To open your ir-editor on the
workbench, See @{"The Menus" Link "The Menus"}.

   This feature is implemented in the following way:

   You can drag an @{i}iff-ilbm@{ui}-picture onto the project/toolbox-window.
This picture will be loaded as background grafik. You can also drop a
project's icon onto the window. Then, this project will be loaded at
once.

   The file type recognition works via the file name. If the name's
suffix is @{b}.iff@{ub}, @{b}.ilbm@{ub} or @{b}.brush@{ub} the editor assumes a picture file. If
the suffix is @{b}.irm@{ub} the editor tries to load a project.


@EndNode

